  "body": "Your guide to the WSJ’s exclusive reporting and analysis.               Is this email difficult to read? View in browser   https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-e-gkkutll-dknirndy-e/                                                                                                   \r\n\r\nSponsored By\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n✏️ Good morning. We’re still putting the pieces together from the shooting at the Washington Hilton on Saturday night. Our reporters and editors, including many who were there as the incident happened, have the latest on  the security flaws [https://www.wsj.com/us-news/trump-shooting-correspondents-dinner-security-e1483305] that exposed President Trump to another gunman and reconstruct  how the incident unfolded [https://www.wsj.com/articles/inside-the-washington-hilton-how-the-shooting-unfolded-5df5e5d8] through maps, photos and videos of the scene.\r\n\r\nIn other D.C. news: King Charles III arrives in the capital today to publicly mark 250 years since a nascent U.S. republic ousted his forebears—and  privately shore up [https://www.wsj.com/world/uk/king-charles-is-on-a-mission-to-salvage-u-k-relations-with-trump-5df933e3] a trans-Atlantic alliance that many fear is fraying.\r\n\r\nEmma Tucker\r\n\r\nEditor in Chief, The Wall Street Journal\r\n\r\nTODAY'S HEADLINES\r\n\r\n1\r\n\r\nChina ordered that Meta’s $2.5 billion acquisition of artificial-intelligence startup Manus be  unwound on national-security grounds [https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-bans-metas-acquisition-of-manus-on-national-security-grounds-71e10c3f].  Elon Musk is an underdog in his  $180 billion fight [https://www.wsj.com/tech/elon-musk-is-an-underdog-in-his-180-billion-fight-against-openai-32a74332] against OpenAI.  California’s  billionaire tax [https://www.wsj.com/politics/policy/californias-billionaire-tax-has-the-signatures-to-make-the-ballot-backers-say-1c2da7bb] has the signatures to make the ballot, backers say.  In Gaza, one city held local elections  for the first time [https://www.wsj.com/world/middle-east/gaza-election-vote-b25d8206] in more than 20 years. The largely symbolic vote gave Palestinians an opportunity to express a desire for change.\r\n\r\nLIVE FROM THE MARKETS\r\n\r\n2\r\n\r\n            LAST CHG %CHG        DJIA Futures      49320.00 -72.00 0.15        S&P 500 Futures      7189.25 -5.50 0.08        Nasdaq 100 Futures      27454.75 19.75 0.07\r\n\r\nSource: Factset, Market data as of 4/27/2026, 6:00:15 AM ET\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n📈 Follow our  live financial coverage [https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-sp-500-nasdaq-04-27-2026] all day.\r\n\r\nLarry Ellison is one of the world’s richest people. He may also be one of the world’s  most indebted men [https://www.wsj.com/finance/larry-ellison-net-worth-wealth-5571ca5d]—even before he guaranteed more than $40 billion for the Warner Bros. deal.\r\n\r\nREAD IT HERE FIRST\r\n\r\n3\r\n\r\nThese simple security flaws exposed Trump to another gunman.\r\n\r\nDespite a visible security perimeter and warnings of tight security, guests said they could enter the Hilton through checkpoints on the surrounding streets by simply showing a dinner ticket or a copy of an invite to one of several predinner receptions. The tickets were reviewed by staff but weren’t scanned and there were no identification checks, attendees said. Guests were able to access the hotel lobby and lower levels without going through security scans, and only passed through magnetometers before they entered the ballroom where the dinner was held. It was  easier to get into the dinner [https://www.wsj.com/us-news/trump-shooting-correspondents-dinner-security-e1483305] than many big sports events and concert venues, report Sadie Gurman, C. Ryan Barber and Isabella Simonetti.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n4\r\n\r\nCorporate America is minting money—and not just in tech and finance.\r\n\r\nBig American companies are piling up profits despite war and consumer anxiety, bolstered by healthy sales growth. With just over one-fourth of S&P 500 companies reporting results for the first quarter, Wall Street’s expectations for earnings suggest big U.S. companies  are far healthier [https://www.wsj.com/business/earnings/corporate-america-is-minting-moneyand-not-just-in-tech-and-finance-0d833898] than wider economic concerns might indicate. War in the Middle East had led economists to rein in growth projections for the year. Consumers—long the engine of the U.S. economy—feel solidly in the dumps. High oil prices act like a tax, dragging down household consumption while boosting inflation. Yet the biggest U.S. public companies are seeing profit and revenue surge, reports Theo Francis.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTake control of your news.\r\n\r\nMake the Journal  your preferred source on Google [https://www.google.com/preferences/source?q=wsj.com] to see more of our award-winning journalism.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n              CONTENT FROM: GOOGLE          How Google AI Is Helping Teachers Make Every Lesson Count   [http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/clk?id=7220875815&iu=/2]\r\n\r\nGoogle AI is helping teachers create lessons that engage students and make learning stick. By empowering teachers with intuitive AI tools, we’re giving educators more time to do what they do best: inspire the next generation of innovators.\r\n\r\nLearn more [http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/clk?id=7220875815&iu=/2]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nEXPERT TAKE\r\n\r\n5\r\n\r\nQ: What is Fed Chair Jerome Powell’s next move?\r\n\r\nWith Kevin Warsh’s confirmation back on track, the question is whether Powell will  give up his seat [https://www.wsj.com/economy/central-banking/fed-chair-powell-confronts-his-final-big-decision-stay-or-go-635eb131] on the Fed’s board next month. Chief economics correspondent Nick Timiraos has the latest on the Fed succession drama:\r\n\r\nA: What’s left unresolved is whether Powell will give up his seat on the Fed’s board when his chairmanship ends or stay on as a governor, a position he can hold until January 2028.\r\n\r\nPowell’s own test for the decision is that the criminal probe into him be “well and truly over, with transparency and finality.” Whether that threshold has been met is unclear.\r\n\r\nIf Powell leaves, Trump gets a second vacancy to fill beyond the seat being used to install Warsh. If Powell stays, Trump has no other scheduled vacancies on the Fed’s board before 2028.\r\n\r\nTrump administration officials have said they hope and expect Powell to follow the tradition of his predecessors and leave.\r\n\r\nPeople who know Powell say that he is more than eager to return to private life. But agreeing to leave soon could, at least implicitly, validate the pressure campaign Powell has spent the past year avoiding.\r\n\r\nStaying would deny Trump another seat from which to challenge institutional norms; leaving would give Warsh room to lead the central bank and the rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee.\r\n\r\nPowell himself hasn’t signaled which way he is leaning, and the small circle of advisers and friends who might know are declining to discuss it. Some who admire the job Powell has done think the right move now is for him to leave if the probe is truly over.\r\n\r\nSEE THE STORY\r\n\r\n6\r\n\r\nWe’re tracking corporate layoffs in 2026.                                           \r\n\r\nWith major employers including Nike, Morgan Stanley and Amazon recently announcing job cuts, anxiety is mounting over AI’s role in upending the workplace. Tech has been hardest-hit this year, with 40% more layoffs in the first quarter—and fresh announcements of another 10,000 positions lost in April, including at Meta and Snap. Here’s how this year’s job cuts  are stacking up [https://www.wsj.com/articles/tracking-corporate-layoffs-in-2026-784ea69f].\r\n\r\nThe AI splurge is  costing big tech its workforce [https://www.wsj.com/tech/ai/the-ai-splurge-is-costing-big-tech-its-workforce-34a88e68], write Dan Gallagher and Asa Fitch.\r\n\r\nHAPPENING TODAY\r\n\r\n7\r\n\r\nElon Musk’s lawsuit against OpenAI is set to begin this week in Oakland, Calif.  King Charles and Queen Camilla arrive in the U.S. for a four-day state visit that will take them to Washington D.C., New York and Virginia.  Earnings: Verizon, Domino’s, Bed Bath & Beyond  📰  Today's paper [http://ereader.wsj.net/?]\r\n\r\nTHE NUMBER\r\n\r\n8\r\n\r\n          $50          \r\n\r\nHow much Regal Cinemas recently charged for opening-night seats in the best theaters to see December’s “Dune: Part Three.” Eye-popping prices for the most in-demand movies on the best screens are  becoming increasingly common [https://www.wsj.com/business/media/the-50-movie-ticket-has-arrived-42251672] as the cinema industry copies the audience-segmentation playbooks of airlines and hotels. Theaters are getting people who love movies and have discretionary income to pay substantially more. Some 17% of film tickets sold last year were for premium-format theaters with bigger screens and better sound, compared with 13% in 2021.\r\n\r\nAND FINALLY...\r\n\r\n9\r\n\r\nThis is how to not get poisoned at a world leaders summit.\r\n\r\nAhead of a May 14-15 summit between Trump and Xi Jinping in Beijing, hundreds of government officials on both sides are racing to make sure the two leaders say the right thing, go to the right place— and don’t get poisoned [https://www.wsj.com/politics/how-to-avoid-fistfights-and-dna-leaks-at-a-world-leaders-summit-051741e8]. It will be the first state visit by a U.S. president to China in nearly a decade, and it comes at a moment of deepening distrust between the two countries. The idea is that nothing goes wrong. The challenge is that so many things can.\r\n\r\nBEYOND THE NEWSROOM\r\n\r\n10\r\n\r\nOpinion: Trump  hits the right notes [https://www.wsj.com/opinion/a-friendly-federal-assassin-in-washington-f9750386] after a third apparent assassination attempt.\r\n\r\nWSJ | Buy Side: See our guide to  the best financial adviser companies [https://www.wsj.com/buyside/personal-finance/financial-advisors/top-financial-advisors-for-retirees] for retirees.\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\nAbout Us\r\n\r\nThe 10-Point is your guide to The Wall Street Journal's reporting and analysis you can't get anywhere else. Your subscription makes our journalism possible.\r\n\r\nToday's newsletter was curated and edited by Morgan Smith and Gary Mitchell in collaboration with Editor in Chief Emma Tucker. Got a tip for us? Here's  how to submit [https://www.wsj.com/tips].\r\n\r\n Unsubscribe [http://www.wsj.com/newsletters?unsub=197&addr=d4ae6d32bd4db70c10900a8884d402000bb7d1fd78e887a1ed41df81457d62ff3e]      Unsubscribe https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-u-gkkutll-dknirndy-s/            Newsletters & Alerts [https://www.wsj.com/newsletters]            Contact Us [https://customercenter.wsj.com/public?url=https://customercenter.wsj.com/view/contactus.html]            Privacy Notice [https://dowjones.com/privacy-notice]            Cookie Notice [https://dowjones.com/cookie-notice]                             Dow Jones & Company, Inc. 4300 U.S. Ro‌ute 1 No‌rth Monm‌outh Junc‌tion, N‌J 088‌52\r\n\r\nYou are currently subscribed as wschenk@gmail.com. For further assistance, please contact Customer Service at support@wsj.com or 1-800-JOURNAL.\r\n\r\nCopyright 2026 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.   |   All Rights Reserved.\r\n",
