l,sans-serif;line-height:30px;\" >\r\nCorporate America is minting money—and not just in tech and finance.\r\n</h3>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;max-width:640px;\" >\r\n<table align=\"center\" role=\"none\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:20px;padding-left:20px;text-align:center;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div class=\"cp100 ogf\" style=\"text-align:left;display:inline-block;width:100%;\" >\r\n<table role=\"none\" width=\"100%\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"left\" class=\"p\" style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:0;padding-left:0;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:16px;line-height:24px;text-align:left;color:#222;\" ><p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tBig American companies are piling up profits despite war and consumer anxiety, bolstered by healthy sales growth. With just over one-fourth of S&amp;P 500 companies reporting results for the first quarter, Wall Street’s expectations for earnings suggest big U.S. companies <a href=\"https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-l-gkkutll-dknirndy-q/\" style=\"text-decoration:underline;color:#015483;\" >are far healthier</a> than wider economic concerns might indicate. War in the Middle East had led economists to rein in growth projections for the year. Consumers—long the engine of the U.S. economy—feel solidly in the dumps. High oil prices act like a tax, dragging down household consumption while boosting inflation. Yet the biggest U.S. public companies are seeing profit and revenue surge, reports Theo F