ace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"left\" class=\"h1\" style=\"margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;font-family:Arial,sans-serif;line-height:30px;padding-top:0;padding-bottom:16px;padding-right:20px;padding-left:20px;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:20px;text-align:left;color:#222;\" >\r\n<h3 style=\"font-size:24px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;font-family:Arial,sans-serif;line-height:30px;\" >\r\nQ:  What is Fed Chair Jerome Powell’s next move?\r\n</h3>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;max-width:640px;\" >\r\n<table align=\"center\" role=\"none\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:20px;padding-left:20px;text-align:center;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div class=\"cp100 ogf\" style=\"text-align:left;display:inline-block;width:100%;\" >\r\n<table role=\"none\" width=\"100%\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"left\" class=\"p\" style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:0;padding-left:0;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:16px;line-height:24px;text-align:left;color:#222;\" ><p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\t<em>With Kevin Warsh’s confirmation back on track, the question is whether Powell will <a href=\"https://10point.cmail19.com/t/d-l-gkkutll-dknirndy-g/\" style=\"text-decoration:underline;color:#015483;\" >give up his seat</a> on the Fed’s board next month. Chief economics correspondent <strong>Nick Timiraos</strong> has the latest on the Fed succession drama:</em></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;max-width:640px;\" >\r\n<table align=\"center\" role=\"none\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:20px;padding-left:20px;text-align:center;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div class=\"cp100 ogf\" style=\"text-align:left;display:inline-block;width:100%;\" >\r\n<table role=\"none\" width=\"100%\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"left\" class=\"p\" style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:0;padding-left:0;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div style=\"font-family:Arial,sans-serif;font-size:16px;line-height:24px;text-align:left;color:#222;\" ><p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\t<span style=\"font-size:18px;\" ><strong>A:</strong></span>&nbsp;What’s left unresolved is whether Powell will give up his seat on the Fed’s board when his chairmanship ends or stay on as a governor, a position he can hold until January 2028.</p>\r\n<p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tPowell’s own test for the decision is that the criminal probe into him be “well and truly over, with transparency and finality.” Whether that threshold has been met is unclear.</p>\r\n<p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tIf Powell leaves, Trump gets a second vacancy to fill beyond the seat being used to install Warsh. If Powell stays, Trump has no other scheduled vacancies on the Fed’s board before 2028.</p>\r\n<p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tTrump administration officials have said they hope and expect Powell to follow the tradition of his predecessors and leave.</p>\r\n<p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tPeople who know Powell say that he is more than eager to return to private life. But agreeing to leave soon could, at least implicitly, validate the pressure campaign Powell has spent the past year avoiding.</p>\r\n<p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tStaying would deny Trump another seat from which to challenge institutional norms; leaving would give Warsh room to lead the central bank and the rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee.</p>\r\n<p style=\"display:block;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:16px;margin-right:0;margin-left:0;\" >\r\n\tPowell himself hasn’t signaled which way he is leaning, and the small circle of advisers and friends who might know are declining to discuss it. Some who admire the job Powell has done think the right move now is for him to leave if the probe is truly over.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div style=\"margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;max-width:640px;\" >\r\n<table align=\"center\" role=\"none\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:20px;padding-left:20px;text-align:center;border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<div class=\"cp100 ogf\" style=\"text-align:left;display:inline-block;width:100%;\" >\r\n<table role=\"none\" width=\"100%\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;mso-table-lspace:0;mso-table-rspace:0;\" >\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align=\"center\" class=\"hr\" style=\"padding-top:20px;padding-bottom:16px;padding-right:0;padding-left: